ool-call markup inside explanatory text; when you decide to call the tool, emit the tool call itself.\nIf you use MOUSE, include integer row and col arguments.\nEFFICIENCY BUDGET \u2014 your score on each level is (baseline_actions / your_actions)^2, so every wasted action costs you quadratically.\nLevel 1: you have used 112 actions; a strong score needs about 39 or fewer. You are 2.9x over the target.\nIf you are not steadily making progress toward the level goal, commit to your single best hypothesis and the shortest sequence that tests it \u2014 do not exhaustively scan rows/columns or enumerate every option. Test one idea, read the result, then decide.", "kind": "tool", "inContext": true}, {"label": "THINKING", "content": "Clicking on the orange background was also no_impact. I've tried almost everything:\n1. Moving the blue bar in all directions\n2. Pressing SPACE at various positions\n3. Clicking on the charcoal block\n4. Clicking on the yellow shapes\n5. Clicking on the orange background\n6. Moving the blue bar to various positions (center, bottom, top, aligned with charcoal/magenta)\nNone of these have completed the level. I need to think about this more carefully.\nLet me reconsider the game mechanics. The blue bar moves in steps of 4 cells. The green bar at the top decreases over time. The charcoal and magenta blocks are fixed. The yellow shapes are fixed.\nWhat if the goal is to move the blue bar to a specific position such that it \"collects\" or \"activates\" something? For example, what if the blue bar needs to be at the same column as the charcoal/magenta blocks (which it already is, cols 32-51 includes cols 36-39), and at a specific row?\nActually, I just realized something. The blue bar is 20 columns wide (cols 32-51). The charcoal/magenta blocks are 4 columns wide (cols 36-39). So the blue bar is centered on the charcoal/magenta blocks: (32+51)/2 = 41.5, and (36+39)/2 = 37.5. Wait, that's not centered. The blue bar's center is at col 41.5, and the 